rs","html_id":"outliers","implicit":true,"key":"W5ncalDQjf"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Outliers","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"gLPHAXR9tD"}],"key":"uavgAkzGBZ"},{"type":"text","value":" are observations that fall outside the overall pattern. For example, the following histogram represents a distribution that has a high probable outlier:","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"zKFNSssXv7"}],"key":"kCSfqJFaxu"},{"type":"container","kind":"figure","children":[{"type":"image","url":"/build/histogram7-9670a07553cbc75c32408c90724c1c53.gif","alt":"A histogram with frequency on the Y-axis. As we go from left to right on the x-axis, the frequency increases to a peak at x=5, then decreases. Eventually, we reach 0 at x=11. All of x &gt; 10 have a frequency of 0, exception for x=15, which has a frequency of greater than zero. This is a outlier.","key":"nLqpWOWvb6","urlSource":"images/histogram7.gif"},{"type":"caption","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":40,"column":1},"end":{"line":40,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A histogram with frequency on the Y-axis. As we go from left to right on the x-axis, the frequency increases to a peak at x=5, then decreases. Eventually, we reach 0 at x=11. All of x > 10 have a frequency of 0, exception for x=15, which has a frequency of greater than zero. This is a outlier.","position":{"start":{"line":40,"column":1},"end":{"line":40,"column":1}},"key":"KJqAuTdvv8"}],"key":"cNUuF1vF5n"}],"key":"jk2jC4RbF0"}],"enumerator":"2","key":"qysP4ntB31"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Go back and check the histogram of scores at the top of this page. As you can see, there are no outliers.","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"key":"sfQrvYmRt3"}],"key":"GWG4dODbtP"},{"type":"admonition","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Example: Best Actress Oscar Winners","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"key":"Pbi4nEYCQ9"}],"key":"J4pqWBm5LF"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"To provide an example of a histogram applied to actual data, we will look at the ages of Best Actress Oscar winners from 1970 to 2013 (To see the full dataset, click here.)\n\nThe histogram for the data is shown below.\n\n```{figure} images/oscar_actress_histogram.png\n```\n\nWe will now summarize the main features of the distribution of ages as it appears from the histogram:\n\n*Shape:* The distribution of ages is skewed right. We have a concentration of data among the younger ages and a long tail to the right. The vast majority of the \"best actress\" awards are given to young actresses, with very few awards given to actresses who are older.\n\n*Center:* The data seem to be centered around 34 or 35 years old. Note that this implies that roughly half the awards are given to actresses who are less than 34 years old.\n\n*Spread:* The data range from about 20 to about 80, so the approximate range equals 80 - 20 = 60.\n\n*Outliers:* There seem to be two probable outliers to the far right and possibly three around 62 years old.\n\nYou can see how informative it is to know \"what to look at\" in a histogram. If there is one conclusion that we can make here, it is that Hollywood likes to give Oscars to young actresses.","position":{"start":{"line":46,"column":1},"end":{"line":63,"column":1}},"key":"RiwyaS7T1F"}],"key":"atq7klxF9d"},{"type":"admonition","kind":"note","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note","key":"ow13GktUPl"}],"key":"lNQCpaRYeN"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"**Learn By Doing**\n\nHistogram\n\n*(Interactive activity — available in the OLI platform)*","position":{"start":{"line":67,"column":1},"end":{"line":71,"column":1}},"key":"fHPjYZw9AL"}],"key":"hGs7sRTLnC"},{"type":"admonition","kind":"note","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note","key":"lQkPkw2yXW"}],"key":"X8MBoLIfMV"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"**Did I Get This?**\n\n*(Interactive activity — available in the OLI platform)*","position":{"start":{"line":75,"column":1},"end":{"line":77,"column":1}},"key":"ZCoPVWRXiS"}],"key":"o67A4IM8tO"},{"type":"admonition","kind":"note","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note","key":"ixoUuMirEv"}],"key":"KzssboIkii"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"**Did I Get This?**\n\n*(Interactive activity — available in the OLI platform)*","position":{"start":{"line":81,"column":1},"end":{"line":83,"column":1}},"key":"fBO7HX5m6N"}],"key":"xQzax5CwTm"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":86,"column":1},"end":{"line":86,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":86,"column":1},"end":{"line":86,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Did You Get It?","position":{"start":{"line":86,"column":1},"end":{"line":86,"column":1}},"key":"XUQ66xgKKb"}],"key":"K7JRkaHDWJ"},{"type":"text","value":" If so, then go ahead and move on to the next page. If not, then click the link below for some additional practice.","position":{"start":{"line":86,"column":1},"end":{"line":86,"column":1}},"key":"SCzxneR7Pr"}],"key":"USuHep7h4K"},{"type":"admonition","kind":"note","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note","key":"AntYGEyppX"}],"key":"A4euHT3Sg3"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"**Did I Get This?**\n\nHistogram (3 of 3): Extra Problems\n\n*(Interactive activity — available in the OLI platform)*","position":{"start":{"line":89,"column":1},"end":{"line":93,"column":1}},"key":"GroRiHJmc6"}],"key":"R3Uxiijnro"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":96,"column":1},"end":{"line":96,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Let’s Summarize","position":{"start":{"line":96,"column":1},"end":{"line":96,"column":1}},"key":"gt1Bjl4iQU"}],"identifier":"lets-summarize","label":"Let’s Summarize","html_id":"lets-summarize","implicit":true,"key":"ekwOR8Zx4T"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":98,"column":1},"end":{"line":104,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":98,"column":1},"end":{"line":98,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"The histogram is a graphical display of the distribution of a quantitative variable. It plots the number (count) of observations that fall in intervals of values.","position":{"start":{"line":98,"column":1},"end":{"line":98,"column":1}},"key":"FjymhCATxu"}],"key":"lAJwelv3hq"}],"key":"F1j48J8ojs"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"When examining the distribution of a quantitative variable, one should describe the overall pattern of the data (shape, center, spread), and any deviations from the pattern (outliers).","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"key":"RuLyia7axl"}],"key":"HzGF1hQvSv"}],"key":"RBAa4oag8a"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":100,"column":1},"end":{"line":102,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"When describing the shape of a distribution, one should consider: Not all distributions have a simple, recognizable shape.","position":{"start":{"line":100,"column":1},"end":{"line":100,"column":1}},"key":"UtbOdoubCs"}],"key":"rXr9CPvG9n"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":101,"column":1},"end":{"line":102,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":101,"column":1},"end":{"line":101,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Symmetry/skewness of the distribution","position":{"start":{"line":101,"column":1},"end":{"line":101,"column":1}},"key":"l0dAdz7gbX"}],"key":"A5tjmDYgSm"}],"key":"dIQsNAc8iE"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":102,"column":1},"end":{"line":102,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Peakedness (modality)—the number of peaks (modes) the distribution has.","position":{"start":{"line":102,"column":1},"end":{"line":102,"column":1}},"key":"Bz8IPT23JK"}],"key":"Ut7bSJ6kCJ"}],"key":"pdpIW3ryVZ"}],"key":"n79CkjeFQ2"}],"key":"r54QpGf04Z"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":103,"column":1},"end":{"line":103,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Outliers are data points that fall outside the overall pattern of the distribution and need further research before continuing the analysis.","position":{"start":{"line":103,"column":1},"end":{"line":103,"column":1}},"key":"KCmw6R1zgE"}],"key":"ekjJla6N5u"}],"key":"wgzjOyhSTv"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":104,"column":1},"end":{"line":104,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"It is always important to interpret what the features of the distribution (as they appear in the histogram) mean in the context of the data.","position":{"start":{"line":104,"column":1},"end":{"line":104,"column":1}},"key":"DE8zG0HdMN"}],"key":"stIxhF3d1e"}],"key":"o5VzLCkWGK"}],"key":"Mn0sfnTEIF"}],"key":"qXW2Z50VBk"}],"key":"pcekd6R3Nh"},"references":{"cite":{"order":[],"data":{}}},"footer":{"navigation":{"prev":{"title":"Histogram (2 of 3)","url":"/pages/m04-histogram-2-of-3","group":"Unit 2: Exploratory Data Analysis"},"next":{"title":"Stemplot","u